MAINTENANCE OF THE WORK
=======================

The Work has the status `author-maintained' if the Copyright Holder explicitly and prominently states near the primary copyright notice in the Work that the Work can be used, modified and/or distributed only under the terms and conditions of the LPPL (as specified in the section CONDITIONS ON DISTRIBUTION AND MODIFICATION above). A Base Interpreter may rely on this status to determine whether it can process the Work.

The Work has the status `maintained' if there is a Current Maintainer who has indicated in the Work that they are willing to receive error reports for the Work (for example, by supplying a valid e-mail address). It is not required for the Current Maintainer to acknowledge or act upon these error reports.

The Work changes from status `maintained' to `unmaintained' if there is no Current Maintainer, or the person stated to be Current Maintainer of the work cannot be reached through the indicated means of communication for a period of six months, and there are no other significant signs of active maintenance.

You can become the Current Maintainer of the Work by agreement with any existing Current Maintainer to take over this role.

If the Work is unmaintained, you can become the Current Maintainer of the Work through the following steps:

1.  Make a reasonable attempt to trace the Current Maintainer (and the Copyright Holder, if the two differ) through the means of an Internet or similar search.
2.  If this search is successful, then enquire whether the Work is still maintained.

    a. If it is being maintained, then ask the Current Maintainer to update the communication information kept within the Work.
    b. If the Work is not being maintained (meaning that the Current Maintainer has agreed to pass maintenance to you), then ask the Current Maintainer to transfer the Work to you.

3.  If the search is unsuccessful or no action to transfer maintenance to you is undertaken, you may announce your intention to take over maintenance. (If the Work is a LaTeX work, this could be done, for example, by posting to comp.text.tex.)

    a. If the Work was previously maintained by a single individual, wait at least six months after making a first attempt to trace the Current Maintainer, and at least three months after a second attempt, before announcing your intention to take over maintenance.
    b. If the Work was previously maintained by a group of individuals, then wait at least six months after making a first attempt to trace any of the Current Maintainers, and at least three months after a second attempt, before announcing your intention to take over maintenance.

4.  Wait for three months after announcing your intention to take over maintenance, and then you may become the Current Maintainer of the Work.


WHETHER AND HOW TO DISTRIBUTE WORKS UNDER THIS LICENSE
======================================================

This section contains important instructions, examples, and recommendations for authors who are considering distributing their works under this license. This section does not contain any of the conditions that must be met when distributing works under this license. Instead, it describes how the license may be applied to any work, and the meaning of the conditions given in the previous sections.

The conditions given in the previous sections are the only conditions that must be met when distributing works under this license.

This license gives conditions under which files of The Program may be distributed and conditions under which modified versions of those files may be distributed. The license is *not* designed for the distribution of programs that contain no files of The Program.

Each file of The Program can bear supplementary and/or superseding conditions on modification of themselves and on the distribution of modified versions of themselves, but *no* files of The Program may bear supplementary or superseding conditions on the distribution of unmodified versions of themselves.

If you do not want the Current Maintainer of your Work to receive error reports, or if you do not want users to be able to contact you directly, you should include your contact information in the Work, and add the following notice near the primary copyright notice: `The Work may be distributed and/or modified under the conditions of the LaTeX Project Public License, either version 1.3c of this license or (at your option) any later version.'

A recommendation on how to clearly state the license conditions that apply to a file is given in the appendix `HOW TO USE THIS LICENSE'.


HOW TO USE THIS LICENSE
=======================

To use this license, place in each of the components of your work both an explicit copyright notice including your name and the year the work was authored and also a statement of the license conditions. For example, if your work is a LaTeX package called `example', the following text (written in the LaTeX package style) could be used:

    %% example.dtx
    %% Copyright (C) <year> <your name>
    %%
    %% This work may be distributed and/or modified under the
    %% conditions of the LaTeX Project Public License, either version 1.3c
    %% of this license or (at your option) any later version.
    %% The latest version of this license is in
    %%   https://www.latex-project.org/lppl.txt
    %% and version 1.3c or later is part of all distributions of LaTeX
    %% version 2008 or later.
    %%
    %% This work has the LPPL maintenance status `maintained'.
    %%
    %% The Current Maintainer of this work is <your name>.
    %%
    %% This work consists of the files example.dtx and example.ins
    %% and the derived file example.sty.

If your work is a LaTeX package, then you should also add the following line at the end of your package:

    \endinput

This will ensure that LaTeX will not process the rest of the file as part of the package.

If your work consists of more files than just `example.dtx' and `example.ins', then you should include in the `example.dtx' file a statement of what other files constitute the work, for example:

    %% This work consists of the files example.dtx, example.ins,
    %% example.pdf, and the derived files example.sty, example.log,
    %% and example.aux.

If you are the Current Maintainer of the work, you may want to include a statement such as the following in the work:

    %% The Current Maintainer of this work is <your name>.
    %%
    %% This work consists of ...


IMPORTANT ADVICE
================

For programs that are generally useful to the LaTeX community, you are strongly encouraged to make your program CTAN-aware. That is, ensure that your program can be installed from the CTAN archives and that it can be used with the standard LaTeX installation tools. CTAN is the Comprehensive TeX Archive Network, the primary source of TeX-related software. See https://ctan.org for more information.

You are also encouraged to submit your work to the CTAN archives. The CTAN team will be happy to help you with this process.

The LPPL is specifically designed to ensure that improvements to the work are fed back to the community. If you have any suggestions for improvements to this license, please send them to the LaTeX Project at https://www.latex-project.org/contact/.
